** in upper-middle and lower-middle-income countries.\n    *   Significantly lower costs in low-income countries.\n*   **Total Addressable Market (TAM):** The company estimates the consumer AI subscription market opportunity at **~$760 billion annually**. This is based on the global population aged 10+ (~5.5 billion) multiplied by a weighted average monthly subscription revenue assumption of $12.\n\n### 4. Grok & AI Monetization Strategies\nBeyond consumer subscriptions, the company is diversifying its AI monetization through several channels:\n*   **Standalone Grok Advertising:** While Grok is currently integrated into X\'s ad ecosystem to help advertisers with campaign creation and creative optimization, management noted a future **"incremental monetization opportunity by introducing advertising into our stand-alone Grok offering."**\n*   **API Access & Data Licensing:** \n    *   The company generates revenue by providing **API access to Grok models** (recognized ratably over contract terms or as services are consumed).\n    *   **Data Licensing:** Selling licensed data to third parties generated $88M in 2025 and $12M in Q1 2026.\n*   **Enterprise & Government Deployments:** The company offers **Grok Business and Grok Enterprise**, which are tailored deployments customized to specific workflows and security needs, sold on license-, consumption-, or outcome-based pricing models.\n*   **Compute Infrastructure Monetization:** The company monetizes its massive gigawatt-scale AI compute infrastructure (e.g., COLOSSUS and COLOSSUS II) by leasing unused capacity to third parties. Notably, they signed a Cloud Services Agreement with **Anthropic** worth **$1.25 billion per month** through May 2029.\n\n### 5. Cost of Revenue & R&D Context\n*   **Cost of Revenue:** AI segment costs are heavily driven by data center facilities, public cloud hosting, and GPU depreciation. In 2025, infrastructure and cloud computing costs rose by $412M due to increased subscriber revenue.\n*  